#check correlations
ggcorr(crime, label = T, layout.exp = 1, cex=2.5)

Looking at the correlation matrix, police_exp59 and police_exp60 are highly correlated to crime rates at 0.7. Additionally, both variables are perfectly correlated to each other. Hence, we need to drop either of the two variables as having both will affect the significance of each predictor in the regression model.
Other variables weakly correlated to crime rates are prob_prison, gdp, state_pop and mean_education. They could be useful predictors. Since gdp and inequality have negative high correlation as well, one of it should be dropped from the model.

Create train and test sets.

set.seed(123)
sample_crime <- sample(nrow(crime), nrow(crime)*0.8)
train_crime <- crime[sample_crime,]
test_crime <- crime[-sample_crime,]

#check train and test datasets size
dim(train_crime)
dim(test_crime)
dim(crime)

Build base model

Base model is built with all the independent variables considered in the regression model. This will be the baseline for comparison with subsequent models. Model performance can be accessed on metrics like R squared and RMSE.

#Base linear model
base_model <- lm(crime_rate ~., train_crime)
summary(base_model)

Model 4 seems like the best model amongst all as it has the highest R squared and lowest RMSE. High R squared mean the predicted values are highly correlated to actual values; the model best predicts the desired results. Also, low RMSE means model 4 has the least errors in prediction results.

Simple diagnostic checks

Diagnostic checks are conducted on model 4 as it is the best model thus far. We assume the predicted results and the predictors have a linear relationship when building the model. However, this may not be true. Hence, diagnostic checks are needed for checking the assumptions made.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model_4)

Residuals vs Fitted: shows a random pattern, which indicates that the linear model provides a decent fit to the test data.
Normal Q-Q: the residuals fairly follow the straight line and are normally distributed, so we can assume normality
Scale-Location: The residuals look randomly spread out along the line. However, along the fitted values, the residuals begin to converge. It seems that there is uneven variance of residuals (heteroscedasticity).
Residuals vs Leverage: All cases are within boundaries of Cook’s distance, hence no outliers which are influential to the regression results. 

#Assess multicollinearity of chosen model
vif(model_4)
##      percent_m mean_education   police_exp60   unemploy_m39     inequality

Since there is no significant multicollinearity, no independent variables need to be further removed from the model.

library(MASS)
library(GGally)
library(caret)
library(leaps)
library(car)
library(skimr)

data("UScrime")
crime <-  UScrime

names(crime) <- c("percent_m", "is_south", "mean_education", "police_exp60", "police_exp59", "labour_participation", "m_per1000f", "state_pop", "nonwhites_per1000", "unemploy_m24", "unemploy_m39", "gdp", "inequality", "prob_prison", "time_prison", "crime_rate")

#load and check data
str(crime)
#check for missing values
summary(crime)
#check correlations
ggcorr(crime, label = T, layout.exp = 1, cex=2.5)

set.seed(123)
sample_crime <- sample(nrow(crime), nrow(crime)*0.8)
train_crime <- crime[sample_crime,]
test_crime <- crime[-sample_crime,]

#check train and test datasets size
dim(train_crime)
dim(test_crime)
dim(crime)

#Base linear model
base_model <- lm(crime_rate ~., train_crime)
summary(base_model)

#prediction using model
predict_1 <- predict(base_model, test_crime)
#comparing actual against prediction values
data.frame(predict_1,test_crime$crime_rate)

#R squared(how correlated predicted and actual values are, the higher the better)
r_1 <- R2(predict_1, test_crime$crime_rate)

#rmse(error rate; avg diff btw predicted and actual values, the lower the better)
rmse_1 <- RMSE(predict_1, test_crime$crime_rate)

#Stepwise method to choose combination with least sum of residuals squared
step_both <- step(base_model, direction = "both")
step_both$call

model_2 <- lm(formula = crime_rate ~ percent_m + is_south + mean_education + 
    police_exp60 + m_per1000f + unemploy_m24 + unemploy_m39 + 
    inequality + prob_prison, data = train_crime)

summary(model_2)

predict_2 <- predict(model_2, test_crime)
data.frame(predict_2,test_crime$crime_rate)

#R squared
r_2 <- R2(predict_2, test_crime$crime_rate)

#rmse
rmse_2 <- RMSE(predict_2, test_crime$crime_rate)

#Adjusted R squared of model has improved from the base model and its p-value is <0.05, hence it is statistically significant. Variable is_south has a p-value >0.05, hence we should try removing it from model.

#try removing variable is_south since it is not significant and generate another model

Findings

Model 4 has 6 predictors considered in the regression model: percent_m, mean_education, police_exp60, unemploy_m39, inequality and prob_prison.
Model 4 is the best model thus far as it has the highest R squared and lowest RMSE values compared to the other models. Furthermore, diagnostic checks done showed that the model follows the assumptions of linearity and normality. There is also no presence of influential outlier cases. However, heteroscedasticity is a problem. Perhaps, more can be done to investigate and transform the variable(s) which cause this problem before generating another regression model. Another problem is the small dataset. There is only 47 observations in the data which makes the model more prone to problems such as overfitting and outliers being influential.
